```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }
        int maxPowerOfThree = (int) Math.pow(3, 19);
        return maxPowerOfThree % n == 0;
    }
}
```

This solution works by attempting to divide the highest possible power of three by the given number. If the given number is a power of three, it should evenly divide 3^19, resulting in a remainder of zero. 

However, please note that due to the precision issues of floating point numbers, using `Math.pow(3, 19)` directly could lead to an inaccurately high value because of how floating point numbers are represented in computers. In most cases for this specific problem, it might still work as expected due to subsequent casting to `int`, but it's not the most accurate approach. A better way would be directly using the known maximum power of three that can be represented by an integer, which is `1162261467` (i.e., `3^19`), as shown below:

```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        int maxPowerOfThree = 1162261467;
        return n > 0 && maxPowerOfThree % n == 0;
    }
}
```

This version circumvents the potential issue with floating point precision and is more to the point in adhering to the constraints of integer arithmetic.

